<HEADLINE>
<P>
EXECUTIVE SUITE: ABC-TV PRESIDENT MANDALA ANNOUNCES RETIREMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Mark Mandala said he will retire as president of the ABC Television Network 
effective May 1. 
</P>
<P>
 Mandala became president in January, 1986, as part of a restructuring by 
parent Capital Cities/ABC. 
</P>
<P>
 In a statement, Mandala, 56, said, "The timing was right, financially and 
functionally, to leave Capital Cities/ABC after nearly 32 years." 
</P>
<P>
 In his job Mandala was in charge of such areas as affiliate relations, sales 
and network operations. He previously worked in such posts as president of the 
ABC-owned television stations division and ABC International Television. 
</P>
<P>
 * Warner Bros. named Mary Murphy director of worldwide promotions. She 
previously was manager of domestic promotions. 
</P>
<P>
 * Alessandro Camon joined the Edward R. Pressman Film Co. as president of 
production. 
</P>
<P>
 * Josh Goldstine has been named Columbia Pictures' vice president of creative 
advertising. 
</P>
<P>
 * Republic Pictures Home Entertainment Group named Dena Wholey vice president 
of marketing. 
</P>
<P>
 Veteran Hollywood executive Lindsley Parsons Jr. was named president of 
International Film Guarantors, one of the few companies left in the dwindling 
business of insuring film productions. 
</P>
<P>
 Parsons most recently was president and chief executive of filmmaker George 
Lucas' Lucas Digital Ltd. and is a former Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer executive. IFG is 
a joint venture of Fireman's Fund and Near North National Group. 
</P>
<P>
 * Largo Entertainment named former Odyssey Distributors President Peter Elson 
as an executive vice president. 
</P>
